If protons interact with polymer chains similar to polyaniline, the doping/de-doping process using $\mathrm{H}^{+}$and $\mathrm{OH}^{-}$should be reversible with the same type of film that was employed herein [16]. To confirm protonic doping reversibility for PEDOT/PSS films, we monitored film absorption at $1600 \mathrm{~nm}$, the Seebeck coefficient, and the electrical conductivity during $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{SO}_{4} / \mathrm{KOH}$ treatment cycles. As shown in Figure 5a, the Seebeck coefficient decreased during the $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{SO}_{4}$ treatment, and the electrical conductivity (Figure 5b) and absorption at wavelengths greater than $1200 \mathrm{~nm}$ (Figure $5 \mathrm{c}$ ) increased. On the contrary, when we treated the film with $\mathrm{KOH}$, the Seebeck coefficient increased, whereas electrical conductivity and absorption at wavelengths greater than $1200 \mathrm{~nm}$ decreased. It is worth noting that the doping and de-doping processes are fully reversible when using the same film. This suggests that protons are capable of reacting with polymer chains even when in a solid state.

